<br>
I don't believe it's a just society that goes around executing people who really had no control over their actions.  Some of the criminally insane, like kleptomaniacs and pyromaniacs for instance, can't control their compulsions.  Those people don't need executions, they need treatment.  Criminally insane murderers often have no concept of right or wrong or in some cases may not have realized the consequence of their actions.  Then there are those people who for some reason or another become so passionately enraged that they lose the ability to think rationally.  It ultimately boils down to whether a person could reason that their actions were right or wrong or lawful.  The retarded especially sometimes lack the ability to judge such things.  Intelligent psychopaths can often judge whether an action they undertake is considered lawful even though they have no moral conscious whatsoever which is why insanity defenses don't work well for them.  Executing people who did something that was out of their control would be akin to executing someone who unwittingly caught a deadly diseased and unknowingly passed it on to other people.  <br>
<br>
